<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-01-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-01-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="184" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d184">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/3577: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_RPS1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-01-03"><hi rend="italic">January 3,
                                1919</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received January 4, 12:49
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Following from [<persName corresp="#p_HEL1">Harris</persName> at]
                            Omsk.</p>
                        <p>“6. 3rd. Ufa has been evacuated by Siberian troops and small detachment
                            Allied troops stationed there. While it is claimed that relinquishing
                            Ufa has no great military signification, yet the moral effect on general
                            situation is not good. <persName corresp="#p_HEL1">Harris</persName>.”</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_RPS1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>